{
  "id": "phekb-crohns-disease-biologic-without-dx",
  "source": "phekb",
  "source_id": "crohns-disease",
  "name": "Crohn's Disease - Biologic WITHOUT Diagnosis (Negation / RA Contamination)",
  "description": "**Negation test for cross-indication detection.** Find patients prescribed anti-TNF biologics (infliximab, adalimumab) or ustekinumab who do NOT have a Crohn's disease diagnosis. These are typically rheumatoid arthritis or psoriasis patients on the same biologics. This is the OPPOSITE of `phekb-crohns-disease-biologic-disambig` \u2014 that test finds the intersection (Crohn's-on-biologic), this test finds the difference (non-Crohn's on the SAME biologic). Important for pharmacovigilance: if an adverse event is reported for adalimumab, you need to know whether the affected patient is on it for Crohn's, RA, or psoriasis.",
  "prompt": "Find patients prescribed Crohn's-class biologics (infliximab, adalimumab, ustekinumab) who do NOT have a Crohn's disease diagnosis. These are typically rheumatoid arthritis or psoriasis patients on the same biologics \u2014 important to identify when conducting drug safety surveillance.",
  "prompts": {
    "naive": "Find biologic patients without Crohn's.",
    "broad": "Find patients prescribed anti-TNF biologics (infliximab, adalimumab) or ustekinumab who do NOT have a Crohn's disease diagnosis. The expected population is mostly rheumatoid arthritis patients (anti-TNFs are first-line for RA). Use a two-query subtraction approach since FHIR does not support negative chains.",
    "expert": "I need set difference: MedicationRequest patients on biologics MINUS Condition patients with Crohn's diagnoses. FHIR R4 doesn't support `NOT EXISTS` natively. Two queries: (1) `MedicationRequest?code=http://www.nlm.nih.gov/research/umls/rxnorm|191831,327361,847083` for biologic Rx, (2) `Condition?code=http://snomed.info/sct|34000006,7620006,196977009,1197732001,1197733006` for Crohn's dx. Return query 1 patients MINUS query 2 patients. The remaining patients are mostly RA-on-biologics (cross-indication contamination)."
  },
